NEW += '                        </div>\n'
NEW += '                        <div class="topic-meta">29 problems &middot; 5 stages &middot; (pos, tight), (pos, tight, prev), (pos, tight, leading, sum), bitmask, value mod K, two tight flags, matrix exp</div>\n'
NEW += '                    </div>\n'
NEW += '                </div>\n'
NEW += '                <div class="topic-body">\n'
NEW += '                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Why This Topic Matters:</strong> Digit DP solves a specific and recurring class of problems: count (or sum) integers in a range [L, R] satisfying a property defined on their decimal (or binary) digits. The core invariant is the prefix-tight constraint: when building a number digit by digit from most significant to least, at each position you are either tight (the prefix so far equals the prefix of the upper bound, so the next digit is limited) or free (the prefix is already strictly less, so the next digit can be anything 0&ndash;9). This boolean flag, combined with whatever property-specific state the problem demands, is the complete state space &mdash; memoisation over it runs in O(digits &times; state_space), typically O(18 &times; small_constant) for Google/ICPC/IOI-level problems. It appears constantly because range [1, 10&sup1;&#8312;] makes brute force impossible, recognisability is low ("count integers with property P"), and the template &mdash; once mastered &mdash; becomes a mechanical frame into which any digit property is slotted.</div>\n'
NEW += '                    <div class="sec-title">The Mental Model</div>\n'
NEW += '                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Digit DP is "controlled digit-by-digit number construction."</strong> You are building the number one digit at a time from left to right, holding a permission slip (the tight flag) that says whether you are still constrained by the upper bound. At each position, you try every valid digit, update the permission slip, update any problem-specific running state, and memoise. The entire range [0, N] is implicitly enumerated in O(digits &times; state) time; [L, R] is answered as f(R) &minus; f(L&minus;1).<br><br>\n'
NEW += '                        <strong>How this mental model scales through the 5 stages:</strong><br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>Stage 1 &mdash; Simplest form:</strong> State = (position, tight). Count numbers &le; N with no extra restriction. Memo table has 18 &times; 2 = 36 entries. Pure mechanical framework.<br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>Stage 2 &mdash; What changes:</strong> One digit constraint added (no two adjacent equal; digits sum &le; K; no digit 4). State gains one dimension: (pos, tight, prev_digit) or (pos, tight, digit_sum). Tight logic UNCHANGED &mdash; only the validity check at each digit placement is new.<br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>Stage 3 &mdash; What expands:</strong> Composite property: two simultaneous constraints, or a running value (remainder mod m, bitmask of used digits, count of a specific digit). State = (pos, tight, leading, extra_1, extra_2). Transitions check ALL dimensions simultaneously.<br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>Stage 4 &mdash; What is hidden:</strong> Problem does NOT say "count integers." It asks for a count of pairs, sequences, or strings &mdash; but counting structure is isomorphic to digit DP after reformulation (digits are bits; tight = lexicographic upper bound).<br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>Stage 5 &mdash; What is optimised:</strong> State space is huge (bitmask over 10 digits = 1024 states, or mod a large prime). Matrix exponentiation collapses O(digits &times; states&sup2;) into O(states&sup3; log digits). Or meet-in-the-middle on digit halves.\n'
NEW += '                    </div>\n'
NEW += '                    <div class="sec-title">Core Invariants / Proof Sketches</div>\n'
NEW += '                    <div class="core-box">\n'
NEW += '                        <strong>Invariant 1: Prefix Decomposition Correctness</strong><br>\n'
NEW += '                        <em>Claim:</em> count(N) = integers in [0, N] satisfying P = solve(pos=0, tight=true, leading=true, extra=initial).<br>\n'
NEW += '                        <em>Proof sketch:</em> (1) <em>Completeness:</em> every integer x &le; N is enumerated by exactly one path through the recursion; at each position i, digit x[i] is chosen. (2) <em>No double-counting:</em> the recursion partitions [0, N] by the FIRST position where the chosen digit is strictly less than bound[i]; at that position, tight becomes false and future digits are free &mdash; creating a disjoint cover of [0, N]. (3) <em>Memoisation validity:</em> the sub-problem (pos, tight=false, leading, extra) is identical regardless of which prefix led to it, because once tight=false, future choices are unconstrained. Only (pos, tight=true, ...) depends on the specific bound. Distinct sub-problems = O(n &times; 2 &times; state_space). &#9633;<br><br>\n'
NEW += '                        <strong>Invariant 2: Range Query via Subtraction</strong><br>\n'
NEW += '                        <em>Claim:</em> count(integers in [L, R] satisfying P) = f(R) &minus; f(L&minus;1) where f(x) = count in [0, x].<br>\n'
NEW += '                        <em>Proof sketch:</em> Let S(x) = set of integers in [0, x] satisfying P. Since S(L&minus;1) &sube; S(R): |S(R)| &minus; |S(L&minus;1)| = |S(R) \\ S(L&minus;1)| = count in [L, R]. Standard inclusion-exclusion for ranges, valid because P is evaluated per integer independently. &#9633;\n'
NEW += '                    </div>\n'
NEW += '                    <div class="sec-title">Sub-Variants to Master</div>\n'
NEW += '                    <div class="info-box" style="line-height:1.75">\n'
NEW += '                        <strong>Group 1 &mdash; Counting with a single digit constraint:</strong><br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>Count integers &le; N with no digit 4</strong> &mdash; Stage 1 | O(18 &times; 2) | (pos, tight) | pure framework; no extra state<br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>Count integers &le; N with no two adjacent equal digits</strong> &mdash; Stage 2 | O(18 &times; 2 &times; 10) | (pos, tight, prev) | ONE new dim: previous digit<br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>Count integers in [L, R] with digit sum = K</strong> &mdash; Stage 2 | O(18 &times; 2 &times; 2 &times; 163) | (pos, tight, leading, sum) | cumulative digit sum; leading zero handling<br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>Digit sum divisible by K</strong> &mdash; Stage 2 | O(18 &times; 2 &times; K) | (pos, tight, sum_mod_k) | sum tracked mod K<br><br>\n'
NEW += '                        <strong>Group 2 &mdash; Digit-set / bitmask constraint:</strong><br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>Using only digits from allowed set</strong> &mdash; Stage 2 | O(18 &times; 2 &times; 2) | check digit &isin; allowed<br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>Using AT MOST K distinct digits</strong> &mdash; Stage 3 | O(18 &times; 2 &times; 2 &times; 1024) | (pos, tight, leading, bitmask_used)<br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>Pandigital (uses all 10 digits)</strong> &mdash; Stage 3 | O(18 &times; 2 &times; 2 &times; 1024) | terminal check mask == (1&lt;&lt;10)&minus;1<br><br>\n'
NEW += '                        <strong>Group 3 &mdash; Modular constraint:</strong><br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>Value &equiv; 0 (mod K)</strong> &mdash; Stage 2 | O(18 &times; 2 &times; K) | (pos, tight, val_mod_K) | recurrence: new_mod = (old &times; 10 + d) % K &mdash; NUMBER mod K, NOT digit-sum mod K<br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>Self-dividing: digit sum divides number</strong> &mdash; Stage 3 | tracks digit_sum AND partial_value<br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>Multiples of K with all digits &le; D</strong> &mdash; Stage 3 | combines val_mod_K with per-digit constraint<br><br>\n'
NEW += '                        <strong>Group 4 &mdash; Sum (not count) over range:</strong><br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>Sum of integers in [1, N]</strong> &mdash; Stage 2 | contribution = d &times; 10^remaining &times; free_count<br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>Sum of digit sums in [1, N]</strong> &mdash; Stage 2 | DP returns (count, sum_of_digit_sums)<br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>Sum of integers &le; N satisfying P</strong> &mdash; Stage 3 | DP returns (count, total_sum) tuple<br><br>\n'
NEW += '                        <strong>Group 5 &mdash; Multi-variable / two-number constraints:</strong><br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>Count pairs (a, b) with digit_property(a XOR b)</strong> &mdash; Stage 4 | TWO tight flags; both numbers built simultaneously<br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>Binary rep: more 1s than 0s</strong> &mdash; Stage 3 | base-2; (pos, tight, leading, ones_minus_zeros)<br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>Base-10 value &equiv; base-B value (mod K)</strong> &mdash; Stage 4 | state = (mod_base10, mod_baseB)<br><br>\n'
NEW += '                        <strong>Group 6 &mdash; Non-adjacent / structural pattern constraints:</strong><br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>No digit d appearing &gt; K times</strong> &mdash; Stage 3 | frequency vector or compressed state<br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>Palindromes &le; N</strong> &mdash; Stage 3 | build outside-in; tight applies to first half only<br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>Strictly increasing digits</strong> &mdash; Stage 2 | (pos, tight, prev) with d &gt; prev<br><br>\n'
NEW += '                        <strong>Group 7 &mdash; Binary / bitwise digit DP:</strong><br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>Exactly K set bits in [L, R]</strong> &mdash; Stage 3 | base 2; 60 bits; (pos, tight, leading, bits_so_far)<br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>A AND x = 0 (no shared bits)</strong> &mdash; Stage 3 | per-bit constraint fixed by A<br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>Maximum XOR of any two numbers in [L, R]</strong> &mdash; Stage 4 | greedy top-down on bits<br><br>\n'
NEW += '                        <strong>Group 8 &mdash; Matrix exponentiation (huge n):</strong><br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>n-digit numbers with no two adjacent equal (n &le; 10^18)</strong> &mdash; Stage 5 | O(10&sup3; log n) | transition matrix exp<br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>Strings length L with property P (L &le; 10^9)</strong> &mdash; Stage 5 | O(states&sup3; log L)<br><br>\n'
NEW += '                        <strong>Group 9 &mdash; Implicit / disguised Digit DP:</strong><br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>Count good strings (LC 2466)</strong> &mdash; Stage 4 | (length, tight_equiv) | recognising equivalence IS the solve<br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>Lexicographic K-th number</strong> &mdash; Stage 4 | count prefixes in lex order + binary search descent\n'
NEW += '                    </div>\n'
