NEW += '                        <strong>&#x1F527; Custom Problem 1: Palindrome Digit DP (S.No 21)</strong><br>\n'
NEW += '                        <em>Statement:</em> Given two integers L and R (1 &le; L &le; R &le; 10^18), count all integers in [L, R] whose decimal representation is a palindrome. Output count mod 10&#8313; + 7.<br>\n'
NEW += '                        <em>Stage:</em> Stage 3 (structural property linking distant positions) + Stage 4 (building outside-in).<br>\n'
NEW += '                        <em>Approach:</em> For each length d = 1..18, count d-digit palindromes in [L, R]. A d-digit palindrome is determined by its first ceil(d/2) digits. Enumerate "half-numbers" h such that mirror(h, d) &isin; [L, R]. This reduces to 1D range count on h in [10^(ceil(d/2)&minus;1), 10^ceil(d/2) &minus; 1], O(ceil(d/2) &times; 2) per length.<br>\n'
NEW += '                        <em>Insight:</em> Palindrome constraint LINKS position i with position d&minus;1&minus;i. Building left-to-right, once first half is fixed, second half is determined. Effective free positions = ceil(d/2) instead of d.<br>\n'
NEW += '                        <em>Example:</em> L=1, R=100. Palindromes: 1..9 (nine 1-digit) + 11,22,..,99 (nine 2-digit) = 18.<br><br>\n'
NEW += '                        <strong>&#x1F527; Custom Problem 2: Matrix Exponentiation Digit DP (S.No 23)</strong><br>\n'
NEW += '                        <em>Statement:</em> Given a positive integer n (1 &le; n &le; 10^18), count all n-digit positive integers (no leading zeros) such that no two adjacent digits are equal. Output mod 10&#8313; + 7.<br>\n'
NEW += '                        <em>Stage:</em> Stage 5 (matrix exponentiation).<br>\n'
NEW += '                        <em>Approach:</em> Let f(k, d) = k-digit numbers ending in d with no-adjacent-equal. Base: f(1, d) = 1 for d &isin; &#123;1..9&#125;, f(1, 0) = 0. Transition: f(k, d) = SUM over d\' &ne; d of f(k&minus;1, d\'). Build 10&times;10 transition matrix T where T[d][d\'] = 1 if d &ne; d\' else 0. Compute T^(n&minus;1) via matrix exponentiation. Answer = SUM over d=1..9 of [T^(n&minus;1) &times; init][d] where init = [0, 1, 1, ..., 1].<br>\n'
NEW += '                        <em>Insight:</em> When n is too large for O(n &times; 10), note the recurrence is LINEAR: f(k) = T &times; f(k&minus;1). Linear recurrences on state vector of size S run in O(S&sup3; log n) via matrix exponentiation.<br>\n'
NEW += '                        <em>Example:</em> n = 2. Answer = 9 &times; 9 = 81 (first: 9 choices; second: 9 choices &ne; first).\n'
NEW += '                    </div>\n'
